properties.description: January 9, 400  Emperor Arcadius, who ruled the Eastern Roman Empire from 395 to 408, gives his wife Aelia Eudoxia the official title of Augusta. She is able to wear the purple paludamentum and is depicted in Roman currency.

In 330, The Roman Empire moved it's capital from Rome to the newly (re)built Constantinople. In 395 The Roman Empire permenantly split into a Western and Eastern half after the death of Roman Emperor Theodosius the Great, when his sons, Honorius and Arcadius were made co-rulers, with Arcadius taking the East and Honorius taking the West. Honorius was the Emperor of the Western Roman Empire from 395 until his death in 423
Hypatia, Greek philosopher, distinguishes herself as one of the first female scientists and becomes head of the Neo-Platonist school at Alexandria.
Rich, the eldest son of Nintoku, becomes the 17th Emperor of Japan.

properties.event: Resurrection and "Two Marys with Angel near the Empty Tomb"
properties.description: Resurrection and "Two Marys with Angel near the Empty Tomb", panel of a diptych, found in Rome, is made. It is now kept at Castello Sforzesco, Milan (approximate date).
Anthemius, praetorian prefect of the East, is sent on an embassy to the Persian capital, Ctesiphon, to congratulate King Yazdegerd I on his accession the year before
